GraphQL with REST API
Tutorial

GraphQL with REST API

6 steps

From the previous tutorials, you have read up on what GraphQL types and resolver functions are and build your first GraphQL API with Node.js and Apollo. In practice, we often do not work with hardcoded data but with REST API endpoints where developers will wrap multiple REST API endpoints into a single GraphQL API for their query. In this tutorial, we will be building a GraphQL API using the Moralis NFT REST API endpoints.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • There are no pre-requisites

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Build a GraphQL API with REST API endpoints

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Bootstrap Your GraphQL API Application

    Before we start building the GraphQL API with REST API, initialise a new directory by running the following command.

    cd Desktop
mkdir rest-graphql
cd rest-graphql

    Open the rest-graphql directory with VSCode. Next, initialise the project by running the following command.

    npm init

    Next, we will install the following dependencies in order for GraphQL to interact with the REST API endpoints. In your terminal, run the following command below.

    npm install apollo-server apollo-datasource-rest graphql-import dotenv

    After installing the dependencies, next we will install nvm. Nvm allows installation of several versions of Node.js as sometimes applications require a certain version of Node.js to work and nvm seeks to provide this flexibility.

    For Windows users, you can head here and download the nvm-setup.exe executable and follow the guide to install nvm.

    For Mac and Linux users, you can run the command below to install nvm.

    brew install nvm

    If you do not have homebrew installed, paste the following code below to install homebrew.

    /bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"

    Upon successful installation, run the command nvm -v and the nvm version number should return indicating a successful installation. With nvm installed, run the following command to switch to Node version 16.

    nvm use 16

    Next, create a new folder titled datasource under the root directory and create a new file nftDatasource.js under the datasource directory. This will serve as the entrypoint to interact with the Moralis NFT REST API endpoints.

  • Step 2: Moralis NFT API Overview

    Before writing the code to interact with the Moralis REST APIs, we will first have to generate an API key from Moralis. If you do not have an account, proceed to sign up and login. Head to the Web3 API section and copy your API key. This API key will allow you to access and interact with the NFT API endpoints.

    We will be wrapping two Moralis NFT APIs namely the Get NFTs by Contract and the Get NFT Transfers by Contract endpoints into a single GraphQL API.

    Before working with any REST API endpoints, it is important to understand what the path parameters are required to make the REST API call, what query parameters are available and how the response output looks like.

    For the Get NFTs by Contract REST API, it will retrieve all the NFTs available from a given contract address including its metadata.

    For the Get NFT Transfers by Contract REST API, it will retrieve all the transfers of the NFT collection. For both REST APIs, the NFT contract address is a required parameter and you should also notice on the response example that the data response is nested where all the fields of interest are stored in the result field.

    With a better understanding of the Moralis NFT API endpoints, head back to your root directory and create a .env file. In the .env file, create a new variable “MORALIS_API” and paste your API key value as shown

  • Step 3: Write NFT Data Source Function

    With your Moralis NFT key generated, we can start writing the NFT datasource functions to interact with the two endpoints. Data sources are classes that the apollo server uses to encapsulate fetching data from a particular source such as from a database or a REST API.

    For this application, we will be using the REST data source from the apollo-datasource-rest library. Copy the following code below to import the REST data source on line 1 of nftDatasource.js.

    const { RESTDataSource } = require(“apollo-datasource-rest”);
    JavaScript

    Next, we will instantiate the contract address required parameter on line 3 of nftDatasource.js with the following code. The contract address provided is the address to the popular NFT collection CryptoPunks.

    // CryptoPunks NFT Contract Address
const contract_address = “0xb47e3cd837dDF8e4c57F05d70Ab865de6e193BBB”
    JavaScript

    With the REST data source imported and the contract address instantiated, we will now write the NFTDataSource class. Copy the following code below on line 6 of nftDatasource.js.

    // NFTData Source class
class NFTDataSource extends RESTDataSource {
 constructor() {
  super();
  this.baseURL = "https://deep-index.moralis.io/api/v2/nft";
 }

 async nftsByContract() {
  return this.get(
   `${contract_address}?limit=10`,
   {},
   {
    headers: {
     accept: "application/json",
     "X-API-KEY": process.env.MORALIS_API,
    },
   }
  );
 }

 async nftsTransfersByContract() {
  return this.get(
   `${contract_address}/transfers?limit=10`,
   {},
   {
    headers: {
     accept: "application/json",
     "X-API-KEY": process.env.MORALIS_API,
    },
   }
  );
 }
}

module.exports = NFTDataSource;
    JavaScript

    You will notice that both REST API URLs are very similar and differ only at the back where the NFT transfers by contract endpoint requires an additional /transfers to the URL. Hence, we included a base URL for better code factoring.

    Next, you should notice that we have 2 async functions nftsByContract and nftsTransfersByContract where we pass in the contract address variable as a required parameter in the URL and the Moralis API Key value under the headers. For the API key value, we use process.env to reference the environment variables from .env to not expose the API key. We also included a query parameter of limit=10 on both endpoints for fast rendering as the default REST API will return 100 values.

  • Step 4: GraphQL Schema and Server Configuration

    Next, create a schema.graphql file on the root directory to map our queries and types related to the REST API calls. Copy the following code below to the schema.graphql file.

    type Query {
 nftsByContract: NFTS!
}

type Query {
 nftsTransfersByContract: TRANSFERS!
}

type NFTS {
 total: Int!
 result: [NFT_META]
}

type NFT_META {
 token_uri: String!
 name: String!
 metadata: String!
}

type TRANSFERS {
 total: Int!
 result: [TRANSFER_FIELDS]
}

type TRANSFER_FIELDS {
 block_number: String!
 transaction_hash: String!
 transaction_index: String!
}
    GraphQL

    You will observe that there are two query types namely nftsByContract and nftsTransfersByContract representing the queries to the two NFT endpoints.

    The nftsByContract query returns a nested response where the result field contains the fields of interest hence the NFTS and NFT_META types are instantiated.

    The same schema design is applied for the nftsTransfersByContract query.

    Hence, we see the benefits of GraphQL API where we can wrap multiple REST API endpoints into a single GraphQL API and we can select our fields of interest through schema definition, ensuring that there is no over fetching of data and eliminating the need to make multiple requests to the different endpoints!

  • Step 5: Initialize GraphQL Server

    With the datasource and schema defined, it’s time to initialise the GraphQL server and execute the queries. Create an index.js file at the root directory and your file structure should look like this.

    Next, copy the following code to index.js file.

    const { ApolloServer } = require("apollo-server");
const { importSchema } = require("graphql-import");
const NFTDataSource = require("./datasource/nftDatasource");
const typeDefs = importSchema("./schema.graphql");

require("dotenv").config();

const resolvers = {
 Query: {
  nftsByContract: (root, _args, { dataSources }) =>
   dataSources.nftDatasource.nftsByContract(),
  nftsTransfersByContract: (root, _args, { dataSources }) =>
   dataSources.nftDatasource.nftsTransfersByContract(),
 },
};

const server = new ApolloServer({
 typeDefs,
 resolvers,
 dataSources: () => ({
  nftDatasource: new NFTDataSource(),
 }),
});

server.timeout = 0;
server.listen("9000").then(({ url }) => {
 console.log(`🚀 Server ready at ${url}`);
});
    JavaScript

    From lines 1 to 4, we import the necessary dependencies such as the apollo-server along with the nftDatasource and type definitions files from the earlier steps. Next, to reference the API environment value from .env, we will configure the dotenv package on line 6.

    The resolver functions start from lines 8 to 15 where when the nftsByContract and nftsTransfersByContract queries are executed, it will run the async functions to call the Moralis REST APIs. Lastly, we initialise the GraphQL server and the server will be booted up at localhost:9000.

    Head to your terminal and run the following code to initialise the GraphQL server.

    node index.js

    After running the above command, head to localhost:9000 and click on “Query your server” to be navigated to the GraphQL playground!

  • Step 6: Run GraphQL Queries

    Under the GraphQL playground, create a new workspace space to execute your queries. Copy the following code below to execute the GraphQL queries.

    query {
 nftsByContract {
  result {
   name
   metadata
  }
 }
 nftsTransfersByContract {
  result {
   transaction_hash
  }
 }
}
    GraphQL

    Next, click on “Run” to execute the queries and you should see that the query has been executed successfully with a status code of 200 and it returns 10 rows of results for the two queries. 

    Congratulations Stackies! You have successfully built a GraphQL API wrapping multiple REST API endpoints! This is no mean feat!
